<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Solusek's eye. Home to the Fire Goblin King himself. It's tightly<br>
winding caverns filled with red mist..<br>
<br>
We found the entrance perched precariously above a bubbling pit of<br>
molten lava. As I made my way along the crumbling rock ledge, I could<br>
feel the fiercely blistering heat radiating from the bottom of the pit.<br>
My feet suddenly felt poorly suited for balance, my heart quailed at<br>
every step. I should have known better than to look down. When I did I<br>
had to tear my eyes from the orange glow of the liquefied rock, its<br>
promise of death was mesmerising. To fall here would mean...<br>
<br>
Struggling to control my fear, I tried to concentrate on my goal, a<br>
small cavern at the end of the ledge, some twenty paces distant.<br>
<br>
After what seemed like an eternity, we were all gathered in the cavern.<br>
A long passage delved into the rock, narrowing out of sight as it<br>
twisted deep into the mountain. Warm air drifted up from the depths,<br>
carrying with it the strong stench of sulphur. Kaelynar's face was<br>
drenched with sweat as he began to describe the route we would need to<br>
take, to find the inferno goblin wizards in their lair. As hot as I was, it <br>
must have been nothing compared to the intolerable heat he must have <br>
felt encased in his plate armour.<br>
<br>
Of the hour that follows, I remember little. Only that the further in<br>
we crept, the more insidious the glow from the rock became. Until it<br>
seemed that the air itself was alive, and possessed with a spirit of its<br>
own. Many goblins fell before us, none of them were potent enough to<br>
match our combined might, and despite their intricate knowledge of the<br>
place they roamed the corridors in scattered groups, never mustering a<br>
significant force to come against us. We slew their wizard conclave,<br>
Hornfell cutting the heart from one of the beast's chest, and wrapping<br>
it in a heavy cloth. The battles, the bloodshed, and the hot oppressive<br>
atmosphere itself lent us an aura of savagery. Looking back it was no<br>
surprise that when we finally came upon the Fire Goblin King, he like his<br>
his priests and bodyguards, was hewn down in quick time, smashed like<br>
kindling beneath Kaelynar's mighty axe, and the sharp blades of Hornfell.<br>
<br>
My memories become clear, when suddenly we realised we were lost.<br>
Somewhere in the midst of these sprawling caverns, we had taken a turn<br>
which Kaelynar knew not. Surrounded by passages, staircases, and<br>
glowing pools of fiery lava, we were alone except for the dripping of<br>
condensation from the jagged roof above us. We had not encountered a<br>
foe for several minutes now. I did not believe for a second that our<br>
foes were vanquished.<br>
<br>
We stood in a large cavern with several entrances. The smoothly faceted<br>
walls of the chamber contrasted starkly with the natural rock above our<br>
heads, orange light from the passages leading out reflected chaotically<br>
from the stone surfaces, gathering intensity until the whole chamber<br>
shone with a lurid orange glow. We were high inside the mountain,<br>
having climbed many sloping passages and roughly hewn staircases. The<br>
air was oppressively, stiflingly hot, making each breath laborious and<br>
inadequate for my body's needs. Standing closer to my water elemental<br>
in an effort to cool myself, I glanced around at my companions.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar stood in the middle of the chamber, indomitable in his finely<br>
crafted armour, his brow furrowed in concentration or confusion. He<br>
scanned the room relentlessly in an effort to jog his memory. The<br>
normally silver edge of his executioner's axe was afire with the orange<br>
glow, not even its enchantement was proof against the light of that<br>
place.<br>
<br>
Soviack watched him with the insipidness that is characteristic of the<br>
Iksar race. His skeletal guardian, gruesome to behold, was off to one<br>
side. It did not stand exactly, but rather seemed to hang in the air,<br>
boned feet barely scraping the ground, as though someone or something<br>
had hammered an invisible spike through its skull, hanging it from the<br>
air itself.<br>
<br>
Hornfell himself looked weary. The effort of swinging the two heavy<br>
blades he held in his gauntleted hands was beginning to take a heavy<br>
toll. Sweat poured from his brow, found its way between the links of<br>
his ivy mail, and glistened incandescent in the orange glow. He stared<br>
into space, making a futile effort to catch his breath.<br>
<br>
Calm Kazzat was just that. Calm. The strain of weaving enchantments<br>
and his near constant healing of the two warriors was evident in his<br>
eyes, but nothing in his stance or in the lines of his face suggested he<br>
was weary, nor in any way concerned. His faith in Tunare was absolute. As<br>
Kaelynar drew confidence from his physical skills and the protection of<br>
his armour, Kazzat drew everything he needed from his trust in his god.<br>
With a faintly benign smile on his lips, he waited calmly for Kaelynar<br>
to speak.<br>
<br>
The air was too warm. It clung to us, played tricks with out minds,<br>
hampered our movements. And it seemed to live, seemed to thrive on the<br>
battles, on the blood we had shed. I could almost hear its secret<br>
whispering, scheming for a way to end our rampage in a murderous finale.<br>
<br>
I was beginning to think I could be losing my mind.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar turned from his inspection of the exits. For perhaps the first<br>
time I have known him, I saw something resembling doubt in his eyes.<br>
Before he even opened his mouth to speak, I knew. We were lost.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not sure where we went wrong, but I do not remember this place.&quot;<br>
He paused, frowning as he regarded each member of the group. &quot;We will<br>
have to take one of these passages on chance.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We trust your judgement Kael,&quot; said Kazzat mildly, &quot;follow your<br>
instincts.&quot;<br>
<br>
Soviack stared at Kaelynar a moment, before regarding each of the exits<br>
in turn. Hissing through his scaled lips, he seemed about to speak, and<br>
then thought better of it. Regarding Kaelynar keenly, he remained<br>
silent.<br>
<br>
&quot;Take one Kael, we need to find a way down quickly.&quot; I said, not<br>
without haste.<br>
<br>
He nodded. Scanning the room once more, his eyes came to rest on a<br>
darker passage, one that sloped slightly downwards. It was opposite the<br>
one through which we had entered.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come.&quot; He said, and strode towards it.<br>
We followed.<br>
<br>
We had barely gone a hundred paces before we stumbled into another<br>
chamber. The only other exit was a passage on the other side. It was<br>
perhaps forty paces away.<br>
<br>
Between us and the passage stood five red skinned goblins. Wrapped in<br>
the ceremonial robes that marked them as magic wielders, eyes shining<br>
hotly with hatred, they blocked our path. We would have to kill them.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar let out a roar as he charged into the room. With his axe held<br>
mightily above his head, he closed the short distance quickly, leveling<br>
a blow which should have crumpled the lead goblin. Faster than a snake,<br>
the goblin leapt aside. Hornfell was only a step behind him however,<br>
and in moments the battle was afoot. Soviak's skeletal pet skimmed<br>
across the ground like a demon, the fire in its eyes reflected harshly<br>
in the rocklight on the walls. Cackling dementedly it picked up one of<br>
the goblins in one clawed hand, raising it above its head.. slamming it<br>
to the ground. There was a crunching of bone, and the goblin lay still,<br>
its back twisted at an unnatural angle.<br>
<br>
My water elemental flew towards them, slammed into the side of one of<br>
the wizards, disrupting his spell. Turning, it lashed out with a<br>
tendril of icy water, coiled it around the arm of the stunned goblin,<br>
tried to drag him to the ground. The goblin was stronger than expected,<br>
however, and planted his feet firmly. With a grimace as the icy tendril<br>
froze the skin of his wrist, he thrust at the elemental with the spiked<br>
tip of his staff. As soon as the staff hit his watery mass, the<br>
elemental began to boil.<br>
<br>
I completed a spell and one of the wizards was suddenly encased in a<br>
cloud of steel slivers. They sliced through his crimson skin, severing<br>
muscle and bone, reducing him to a gory mess of blood and tissue.<br>
Staggering from the after effects of the spell, I could barely hear<br>
Soviack's sibilant chanting, the diminished clash of battle, and too late I<br>
realised Kazzat's danger.<br>
<br>
Kazzat had skirted the room at a run, trying to get into a position<br>
where he could level lightning at the beasts. A position where Kaelynar<br>
and Hornfell were not at risk. As my eyes blurred from the mana flowing<br>
from my body, as my victim fell in a mess on the stone floor, Kazzat's<br>
foot disappeared beneath the granite. Too late for me to shout a warning,<br>
he plummeted through the illusion of rock, and with a distant thud<br>
landed somewhere below.<br>
<br>
As if on cue, five or six goblin warriors charged into the room from the<br>
passageway opposite. As the last goblin wizard fell beneath Kaelynar's<br>
axe, they charged like wild animals at the woodelf and swordwielding<br>
ranger. Bracing themselves to meet the attack, the two warriors were<br>
ignorant to Kazzat's sudden plight.<br>
<br>
&quot;Get us out of here!!&quot; I shouted to Kazzat. I had to send my elemental<br>
to help the warriors. Looking around frantically, it was gone. Not<br>
dead, I would have felt that, but gone. Horror dawned on me. It must<br>
have fallen through the floor with Kazzat.<br>
<br>
Two of the goblins were busy hacking at the Skeleton pet. It's strength<br>
was prodigious, it's speed phenomenal, but the goblins were skilled.<br>
And there were two of them. When the skeleton hauled one of the goblins<br>
up into the air, the other caved in its kneecap with a savage blow,<br>
knocking the undead creature to the ground. While the first goblin<br>
rolled clear, the other brought his heavy mace down on the pet's spine,<br>
splitting it in two. Breaking the enchantment. A second later, the<br>
goblin's skin withered as a furious Soviack sucked the life from the<br>
creature's body. Screaming incoherently, the goblin was reduced to<br>
little more than a dried bag of bones.<br>
<br>
The battle in the centre of the room was furious. Badly outnumbered,<br>
Kaelynar and Hornfell fought like demons trying to stay alive. Between<br>
parrying and dodging their opponents attacks, there was no little time<br>
for either to land a blow. I had to do something, and I had to do it<br>
fast.<br>
<br>
Summoning spikes of steel, I rained it down on the whole group.<br>
<br>
It hurt them, disrupted their attacks. In the space between one<br>
heartbeat and the next, Kaelynar's flow changed from defensive to<br>
aggressive. Spinning on one heel, he brought the blade of his axe<br>
around in a low sweep which cut the legs out from under one of the<br>
goblins. But the ground was slick with blood, and his maneuver was<br>
desperate, too desperate. Unable to maintain his balance against the<br>
enourmous weight of the axe, his boot slipped from under him and he<br>
crashed heavily to the ground.<br>
<br>
Enraged by my spell, three of the goblins ignored him, leapt over his<br>
armoured form. Their eyes full of hatred they covered the ground<br>
between us too quickly for me to run. I blocked one sword with my<br>
stein, the second missed my abdomen by a hair, but the third struck me a<br>
blow to the side of my head which hammered me to the ground. The orange<br>
rocklight exploded like fireworks in my eyes, and I saw a cruel smile filled<br>
with pointy teeth, as the first goblin lifted his sword to end my<br>
life...<br>
<br>
Hornfell waded into them from behind.<br>
<br>
Swinging his blades like a madman he decapitated the first, dealt the<br>
second a savage cut to his thigh, forced the third to turn around, face<br>
him. His face was murderous, his fatigue suddenly gone. Smashing aside<br>
a badly timed swing from the goblin, he brought his second sword around<br>
in an arc that cut halfway into the goblin's chest.<br>
<br>
Blood gushed from the wound, splashing against the wall, drenching my<br>
face and hair. It seemed to claw at my skin, burning my flesh, snapping<br>
me into wakefulness. My head was still ringing with the blow as I<br>
rolled to my feet. I couldn't have been hit that hard.. Could I? And<br>
then I realised. My elemental had been destroyed.<br>
<br>
Clawing at my eyes, I tried to clear the blood from my face. It was<br>
hot, but not damaging. I almost panicked as I remembered there was<br>
still one goblin left. Looking around wildly I saw the withered corpse<br>
at my feet, and realised what had happened - Soviack had drained its<br>
life.<br>
<br>
I could still hear the sounds of battle. Close. Kaelynar had regained<br>
his feet, and was scanning the room. Hornfell, his eyes vivid, stood<br>
ready to face anything. Battle..<br>
<br>
&quot;Kazzat!&quot; I shouted.<br>
<br>
A faint cry came.<br>
<br>
&quot;Help me!&quot;<br>
<br>
With a snarl Kaelynar turned towards the illusionary floow.<br>
<br>
Soviack stared down the passage opposite the one we had entered.<br>
Softly, he hissed..<br>
<br>
'More comesss.' Following his gaze, my heart jumped. Pouring from the<br>
mouth of the passage were too many, too many, goblins. I couldn't count<br>
them all. With a sinking feeling in the pit of my stomach, I knew we<br>
were doomed. They had mustered a sizeable force against us. We had<br>
killed their king, and now they wanted our blood.<br>
<br>
They slowed as they entered the chamber, there were too many.<br>
<br>
They didn't need to hurry.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar, poised on the brink of the pit, turned. The dilemma was plain<br>
on his face. They were too numerous, too many. We couldn't possibly<br>
fight them in this room. His armour dented in many places, Kaelynar<br>
stood motionless, despair in his eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Go!, Sssave him!' Soviack snapped.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar flung a look at Hornfell. I have no idea what passed between<br>
them at that moment, but after an immeasurably short amount of time,<br>
Hornfell gave a curt nod.<br>
<br>
&quot;Go. I will hold them.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kaelynar jumped through the floor.<br>
<br>
Howling, the goblins charged.<br>
<br>
Adrenaline fed our muscles. Moving more quickly than I would have<br>
dreamed imaginable, we leapt backwards into the passage. Hornfell stood<br>
near the entrance, bloodied blades in each hand, Soviack and I behind.<br>
<br>
They would have to cut through Hornfell to reach us.<br>
<br>
There were too many, they would do it.<br>
<br>
For the next few minutes, life held a unique clarity. I remember every<br>
stroke of Hornfell's swords, every scream of each of the goblins. Every<br>
blow that struck the ranger, tearing his armour, rending the flesh<br>
beneath. I summoned steel, and more steel. I summoned steel to rend<br>
their flesh until I was so weak my head swam with dizziness. Many,<br>
many, fell beneath the might of Soviack, drained of life, twitching from<br>
the deadliness of his poisons, spasming as disease took hold of them,<br>
reduced their bodies to writhing masses of sores which formed in front<br>
of my eyes. And when Hornfell staggered, bleeding from many wounds, and<br>
one of the goblins leapt over him to thrust a blade through Soviack's<br>
shoulder, I dispatched it with a blow to the back of its skull, as though I had <br>
been training all my life for just such an action.<br>
<br>
We would have fallen then, but Hornfell summoned strength from the last<br>
vestiges of his soul, staggered to his feet for long enough for Soviack<br>
to form a necromancers pact. Reversing the usual flow of sucking the<br>
life from his victims, the necromancer fed his strength directly into<br>
the ranger. In moments, his wounds began to close, vigour and colour<br>
returned to his face.<br>
<br>
It was enough. Renewed, Hornfell fought once again like a storm in full<br>
fury. Howling with fear and rage, goblins charged and died on his<br>
swords. The air was no longer a lurid orange, it was red with blood.<br>
<br>
But Soviack was sorely wounded. Bleeding heavily from his shoulder, he<br>
had given too much of his strength. He was fading rapidly. Already he<br>
was on his knees, clutching feebly at his wounded shoulder.<br>
<br>
&quot;Drain them!&quot; I rasped at him, indicating the goblins. &quot;Save yourself!&quot;<br>
<br>
The Iksar slowly shook his head. &quot;I.. too weak..&quot; he murmured. I could<br>
barely understand him. &quot;I. I cannotss. sstand.&quot;<br>
<br>
Drained myself, I almost didn't hear him. With the last of my strength<br>
I lifted him to his feet. He was heavy, heavier than I was. Something<br>
fueled our spirits though, allowed us to find strength in the face of<br>
what had looked to be certain death.<br>
<br>
Swooning, and barely able to keep his feet underneath him, even with my<br>
support, the Necromancer began to cast a spell. As the few remaining<br>
goblins ran frenzied to hurl themselves onto Hornfell's blades, Soviack<br>
somehow found the strength to drain the life from one of them. As the<br>
goblin fell, a withered and rotten husk, the wound in the Iksar's scaled<br>
shoulder closed over, and he slumped the the floor breathing harshly.<br>
<br>
At least he was breathing.<br>
<br>
Moments later Hornfell finished the last Goblin.<br>
<br>
He was alive, but barely. If Soviack had not fed him strength, we all<br>
would have died. His armour was ruined, it would need serious repair.<br>
One of his blades was notched in several places. The other had been <br>
broken near the tip. It was a full three inches shorter than it had been.<br>
<br>
But the light in his eyes still shone.<br>
<br>
The sounds of battle below us had stopped. I closed my eyes wearily. If<br>
Kaelynar and Kazzat had not been able to dispatch whatever foes assailed<br>
them, we were doomed. Surely our foes knew the layout of this place, they<br>
would have no trouble finding us, and our strength to fight was all but<br>
gone.<br>
<br>
The stench of sulphur stained my nostrils, engorged my lungs. I did not<br>
want to die in this place.<br>
<br>
There was a scraping of metal on stone. I heard a grunt.<br>
<br>
Kaelynar!<br>
<br>
Opening my eyes, I looked back into the chamber. The unmistakable visage<br>
of the woodelven warrior was strained as he heaved himself through the<br>
illusionary stone floor, and rolled onto his back. His armour cracked and<br>
dented, its ornate finery scored with rents, he looked like a man who had<br>
spent a lifetime on a battlefield.<br>
<br>
Tied securely to his waist was a length of rope. It hung down into the pit<br>
where Kazzat had fallen. First came Kazzat's hand, and then his head, as he<br>
hauled himself out of the pit. Breathing heavily, covered in blood, he<br>
sagged to the floor alongside the warrior.<br>
<br>
My mouth was dry from the incessant heat. I had to moisten my lips several times,<br>
swallow repeatedly, before I could produce a sound from my throat.<br>
<br>
&quot;Kazzat..&quot; I begged. &quot;Get us out of here..?&quot;<br>
<br>
Weary beyond belief, sorely wounded by his struggles, It took him a few moments<br>
to reply.<br>
<br>
&quot;Of course Amethyr, ..of course.&quot;<br>
<br>
